-BAE4-F38A8B49D8D9</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Naomi</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Claire</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Head</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FG00725X%2F1"><gtr:id>C53128B9-870F-4DD1-B40A-1CAA9EFF4037</gtr:id><gtr:title>Conflict, Dialogue and Ethics in International Relations: From the Responsibility to Protect to a Responsibility to Discuss?</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G00725X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>There has been increasing interest in the joint concepts of responsibility and legitimacy in relation to responding to and preventing conflict originating with and resulting in mass human rights violations. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>This research considers how these problems may be addressed through dialogue and problematises existing conceptions of dialogue institutionalised within international structures such as the UN Security Council. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The research presents valuable insights into the nature of distortions in the communicative process and suggests the need for closer attention to be paid to the construction as well as the content of dialogue. The research offers a critical discussion of processes of inclusion and exclusion and, building on existing research into discourse ethics and communicative processes within critical theory and international relations, moves to apply the resulting theoretical framework to humanitarian military intervention in Kosovo. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>This case study highlighted the nature of communicative distortion present within decision-making processes in the Security Council and during peace negotiations leading up to the decision to intervene and, crucially, developed a detailed understanding of the concept of deliberative legitimacy.&amp;nbsp; Having focused on the dialogical approach in Kosovo, these findings may be applied to the study of the legitimacy of decision-making processes in international politics more widely.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-09-15</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-09-16</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>58032</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>F622F880-75B4-49C9-B9FA-95CC25C75C65</gtr:id><gtr:title>Justifying Violence: Communicative Ethics and the Use of Force in Kosovo</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/df383034d8178ee1b26ffb7f9e776121"><gtr:id>df383034d8178ee1b26ffb7f9e776121</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Head Naomi</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2012-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:isbn>9780719083075</gtr:isbn><gtr:outcomeId>i_78711506673b8f2b6e</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>E4D7D122-0909-4E31-A2CE-6DF7842F10E8</gtr:id><gtr:title>Critical theory and the language of violence: exploring the issues</gtr:title><gt